# Copy to `.env` in the repo root. Loaded automatically when you run
# `black-company-telegram` with `pip install -e ".[telegram,llm]"` (python-dotenv).
# Natural-language team + PM copy uses DeepSeek when DEEPSEEK_API_KEY is set.
# Never commit real keys.
#
# --- Local vs Docker ---
# • **Local CLI** — `.env` is loaded first; optional `.env.local` is loaded next and overrides (same keys).
#   Put **host-only paths** in `.env.local` (e.g. `BLACK_COMPANY_DATA_DIR`, `BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECT_ROOT`)
#   so `.env` stays the same on every machine. Docker ignores those paths when Compose overrides them.
# • **Docker Compose** — `env_file: .env` loads secrets, then the service `environment:` block overrides
#   variables for the container (e.g. BLACK_COMPANY_DATA_DIR=/data, BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECT_ROOT=/projects).
#   Use a bind mount for `/projects` (or whatever path you set). Compose `environment:` wins over `env_file`.
#
# DEEPSEEK_API_KEY=sk-...
# BLACK_COMPANY_DISABLE_DEEPSEEK=1
# BLACK_COMPANY_DEEPSEEK_TELEGRAM_ONLY=1
#   — only PM intro + run recap call DeepSeek; graph uses templates (much lower API use).
# DEEPSEEK_MODEL=deepseek-chat
# DEEPSEEK_BASE_URL=https://api.deepseek.com
#
# Org context (optional — injected into PM Telegram / DeepSeek prompts)
# BLACK_COMPANY_NAME=Black Company
# BLACK_COMPANY_BLURB=We build internal PM-workflow and multi-agent demos.
# BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECTS=Telegram hub, LangGraph delivery graph
#
# Existing repos: point at a folder that contains one subfolder per project (read first in PM context).
# Local: D:\path\to\all-repos   Docker: mount that host path to e.g. /projects and set:
# BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECT_ROOT=/projects
# BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECT_ROOT=D:\path\to\all-repos
#
# Run a repo from Telegram: put `examples/dot-black-company-run.toml` in a project as `.black-company-run.toml`, then /runproj
#
# Merge env from Telegram into a project folder:
#   /setenv ProjectName  →  next message is KEY=value lines (writes/merges project/.env under BLACK_COMPANY_PROJECT_ROOT)

# Growth memory (milestones SQLite).
# • Local: omit → `./data` next to where you run the bot, OR set an absolute path (best in `.env.local`):
#     BLACK_COMPANY_DATA_DIR=D:\path\to\data
# • Docker: do not put a Windows path in `.env` for this — `docker-compose.yml` sets
#     BLACK_COMPANY_DATA_DIR=/data (named volume). Only change that if you customize Compose.
#
# User ship stub: `ok` (default) or `concerns` — latter records a growth lesson and
# routes PM back to building/pair. Real user agent should call record_lesson on concerns.
# BLACK_COMPANY_USER_SHIP_STUB=concerns
#
# Telegram (pip install -e ".[telegram,llm]" or Docker; image includes llm extra)
# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=123456:ABC-from-BotFather
# TELEGRAM_ALLOWED_USER_IDS=123456789,987654321
#
# --- Git (private repos — `docker compose exec` into container; token is an env var, not in URLs in git history if you use env) ---
# Put the PAT in `.env` so Compose injects it into the container (`env_file`). Do not commit it.
# GitHub: classic PAT **`repo`** scope → clone + push. Fine-grained → **Contents: Read and write** on that repo for read/write.
#   GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_xxxxxxxx
#   Then inside the container (`docker compose exec telegram sh`):
#     cd /projects
#     git clone https://x-access-token:${GITHUB_TOKEN}@github.com/OWNER/REPO.git
#   (Bash expands $GITHUB_TOKEN; ensure you use `sh` or `bash` with env available.)
# GitLab:
#     git clone https://oauth2:${GITLAB_TOKEN}@gitlab.com/group/project.git
#
